          "cholesterol",
          "red blood cell count",
          "Indole-3-carbinol",
          "estrogen"
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Currently, the patient is dosing 140 ng/dL of testosterone per week and inquired if his dose could be increased to 175 ng/dL. He recalled that he had recently injected testosterone before his last testosterone blood work was performed; last testosterone levels were greater than 1500 ng/dL. The patient confirms continued daily use of Finasteride and Cialis, prescribed by me, and stated he needs a refill for both.\nMr. Edwards mentioned he is taking correct steps to get his life \"together.\" He also uses a med calendar to help with medication compliance.\nPAST HISTORY\nMedical\nHIV\nSOCIAL HISTORY\nUtilizes med calendar to support medication compliance.\nActively trying to get his life together.\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS\nCialis 5 mg tablet by mouth on days he exercises, 2.5 mg tablet by mouth on days without exercise.",
        "medical_concepts": [
          "testosterone",
          "testosterone blood work",
          "testosterone levels",
          "Finasteride",
          "Cialis",
          "HIV",
          "medication compliance"
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Finasteride 5 mg half tablet daily.\nTestosterone cypionate 140 mg.\nRESULTS\nPSA 0.6 ng/mL.\nTriglycerides 145 mg/dL.\nTotal testosterone 1500 ng/dL, 11/24/2021.\nASSESSMENT\n• Hypogonadism.\nPLAN\nI recommend maintaining current management. The patient’s last testosterone levels were greater than 1500 ng/dL, although this level was likely related to his recent injection. He requested an increase to his testosterone cypionate from 140 mg to 175 mg, which I denied due to his already high testosterone levels. I counseled the patient on the risks associated with high testosterone levels and Indole-3-carbinol and it’s lacking evidence to support his estrogen levels. The last time his estradiol levels were checked, they were normal; recommend annual screening.",
        "medical_concepts": [
